memory_of_audio_content:
1. Lives in a small town with a brother Tom and sister Susan (15 min drive away)
2. In college he "helped" his friend on the final exam
3. He believes in chivalry (but in a reasonable context--if there's a heavily pregnant woman on the bus, he'll give up his seat for her)
4. He just moved to a new apartment
5. On the weekends he spends time helping his grandmother because he wants to spend as much time with her as he can while she's here
hypothesis_awareness: I'm not sure--maybe about how if you've "encountered" someone previously you're more likely to have a positive impression of them rather than a negative one?
influence_awareness: I wanted to know what Chris meant that he "helped" his friend in the final exam. Initially I interpreted this as a veiled reference to cheating. But then Chris said that he and his friend would have both failed had he not done so, and it seemed more like Chris had helped his friend in a legitimate way by studying together. It's a good example of how not being able to actually "speak" to the person can skew your impressions. I do think it's best to withhold judgment until you know more about someone.
deepfake_audio_check: Oh no, I didn't know that! Wow, that's interesting. I guess it was audio only, so I suppose that's easier to pull off than those deepfakes where they put someone else's face on another's.
deepfake_concept_check: Nope! No idea. I thought deepfaking referred to a process of matching faces to other faces. But I suppose the point is that digital manipulation is very possible. (Chris sounded like a nice "Australian" guy perhaps? But to be self-deprecating I'm an ignorant American and not great with accents.)
issues_with_study: No issues! (Just that there is a potentially ambiguous reading of what it means for Chris to have "helped" his friend in the final exam--I do think he means it benignly rather than indicating to the fact that he's cheating. Sorry, I've been a university lecturer for too many years and am hyper-vigilant to insinuations of cheating. I did try to disregard my work background and just perceive it as a normal listener would.)
